              <div class="col-lg-12">
                <h4>What is a Sensor?</h4>
                <p>A sensor is any IoT device. In other words, any electronic device that is able to be triggered because of external events, and when that happens it&#39;s able to send URI requests to this website.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="row">
              <div class="col-lg-12">
                <h4>What types of Sensors exist?</h4>
                <p>As long as it can send URI requests, implementation is up to you. It can be a piece of software, it can be an Arduino-based device, it can be a smartphone app, it can even be a camera with AI engine that is set up to send certain repetitions to your account once it sees some kind of object in front of it.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="row">
              <div class="col-lg-12">
                <h4>How to set up a Sensor?</h4>
                <p>In your account, click &quot;Add a new Sensor&quot; button. It will generate API Key &amp; Secret. Then get a device (E.g. Arduino), and tell it to send a JSON API request to our website every time it&#39;s triggered. An example of such code would be:</p>
                <blockquote class="blockquote">
                  <p class="mb-0" style="font-size: 15px;">def activate<br/>  if triggered?<br/>    send_request(json_data);<br/>  end<br/>end<br/><br/>def json_data<br/> {<br/>    API_Key: &quot;9s8v7f9s8f7vsss&quot;;<br/>    API_Secret: &quot;ksjfvnksdfnveknk34n3kj3n&quot;;<br/>    event_name: &quot;My Door Sensor Was Triggered&quot;;<br/>    event_description: &quot;Someone opened a door&quot;;<br/> }<br/>end<br/><br/>def send_request(data)<br/>  %x(curl -d &quot;#{data}&quot;)<br/>end<br/></p>
                  <footer class="blockquote-footer">ruby code example</footer>
                </blockquote>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="row">
              <div class="col-lg-12">
                <h4>What can be a trigger?</h4>
                <p>In Arduino board there is an entire world of sensors available (photo sensors, motion sensors, buttons, chemical sensors etc). Most of them are Plug &amp; Play. Or if you use a camera capable of AI object recognition, you add a code to it like so:</p>
                <blockquote class="blockquote">
                  <p class="mb-0" style="font-size: 15px;">def ai_recognized_an_object<br/>   object_name = AILibrary.recognize<br/>   activate(object_name)<br/>end<br/><br/>def activate(object_name)<br/>  if triggered?<br/>    send_request(json_data(object_name));<br/>  end<br/>end<br/><br/>def json_data(name)<br/> {<br/>    API_Key: &quot;9s8v7f9s8f7vsss&quot;;<br/>    API_Secret: &quot;ksjfvnksdfnveknk34n3kj3n&quot;;<br/>    event_name: &quot;Sensor saw a #{name}&quot;;<br/>    event_description: &quot;#{name} appeared in front of a camera&quot;;<br/> }<br/>end<br/><br/>def send_request(data)<br/>  %x(curl -d &quot;#{data}&quot;)<br/>end<br/></p>
                  <footer class="blockquote-footer">ruby code example</footer>
                </blockquote>
              </div>
